{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20702"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20702"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.08,0.04,0.62,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95610"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13578"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78421"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11762"},{"type":"tags","id":"11768"},{"type":"tags","id":"12579"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95610"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing vascular injury, platelets interact with exposed subendothelial connective tissue to form a platelet plug, which is essential for primary haemostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial step in platelet plug formation after vascular injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Secretion of dense granule contents","Thromboxane A2 production","Conformational change in glycoprotein IIb/IIIa","Binding of glycoprotein Ib to von Willebrand factor","Fibrinogen-mediated platelet bridging"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe initial step in platelet plug formation after vascular injury is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding of glycoprotein Ib to von Willebrand factor\u003C/strong\u003E. This interaction mediates platelet adhesion to the subendothelial matrix, which is the first critical event in the haemostatic process. Genetic deficiencies of von Willebrand factor (von Willebrand disease) or glycoprotein Ib (Bernard-Soulier syndrome) result in bleeding disorders, highlighting the importance of this interaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent subsequent steps in platelet plug formation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of dense granule contents\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after platelet adhesion and activation. Dense granules contain ADP, which promotes further platelet recruitment and activation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConformational change in glycoprotein IIb/IIIa\u003C/strong\u003E happens during platelet activation, after the initial adhesion. This change increases the receptor\u0027s affinity for fibrinogen.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinogen-mediated platelet bridging\u003C/strong\u003E is part of platelet aggregation, which follows platelet activation. Fibrinogen binds to activated glycoprotein IIb/IIIa receptors on adjacent platelets.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThromboxane A2 production\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during platelet activation and serves as an amplification mechanism to recruit additional platelets to the site of injury.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sequence of events in platelet plug formation is: adhesion (via glycoprotein Ib-von Willebrand factor interaction), activation (shape change and granule secretion), and aggregation (fibrinogen-mediated platelet bridging via glycoprotein IIb/IIIa).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Platelet adhesion is primarily mediated by interactions between glycoprotein Ib (GpIb) and von Willebrand factor in the subendothelial matrix.","Platelet activation involves shape change, secretion of granule contents, and conformational changes in glycoprotein IIb/IIIa.","Platelet aggregation occurs when fibrinogen binds to activated glycoprotein IIb/IIIa receptors, forming bridges between adjacent platelets."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 120."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78421"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78421"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-28T19:04:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T19:05:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13578"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95610"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11762","links":{"self